    <p class="section-headers__new-section" id="our-experience">
        <span><i class="fa fa-thumbs-up fa-lg"></i> Our experience</span>
        <p>Make sure you plan the time of the year you will travel based on what type of activities you want to do. If you want to trek, June to September are the best months, but from April to November you will find a heavy fog over the coast, especially Lima. </p>
        <p>You will find that Peru is much more tourist driven in general. This makes travelling through Peru much easier than the other countries. Also, if you are coming from Bolivia you will find a huge improvement in travel (busses especially) quality. </p>
    </p>

	<p class="page-design__our-experience">
        <span>The Good</span>
		<ul class="page-design__our-experience--list">
            <li><strong>Peru is full of natural and manmade beauty. </strong> Whatever you’re into you will find something to suit you. </li>
            <li><strong>Machu Picchu.</strong> It goes without saying, but there’s a reason people will travel across the world to see this world wonder. No matter how many pictures you’ve seen, it will still astound you.</li>  
            <li>It’s good for the budget unless you are in very touristy areas. </li>    
        </ul>
	</p>
    <p class="page-design__our-experience">
        <span>The Bad</span>
        <ul class="page-design__our-experience--list">
            <li><strong>You will get ripped off if you allow it.</strong> Make sure you are bargaining almost everything you do, especially when it comes to tours.</li>
            <li>As always, <strong> do your research on every tour company. </strong> Many will rip you off or just straight up lie to you for your business. Always look the agencies up on TripAdvisor and read the reviews. Consequently, leave yourself at least a day or two to do your research before booking.</li>  
            <li>Certain places can be very touristy, but usually it is for good reason. As a whole, <strong>it was more of a tourist destination than the other countries we visited.</strong></li>
            <li>The food is much of the same, although a step up from Bolivia. You will still find that everything is fried with two starch sides. </li>    
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p class="page-design__our-experience">
        <span>The Verdict</span>
        <p class="section-headers__line-highlight section-headers__line-highlight--smaller">
            <strong>Peru is a must-see in your lifetime. </strong> Obviously many people come just for Machu Picchu, and if you can only do one thing then that’s it, but there is so much to Peru. Allow yourself time to explore and really soak in the culture and beauty Peru has to offer.  
        </p>
    </p>
